body:
Hi:

This is a issue very similar to #2576 

Testcase:
```verilog
module t (
    input          clk,
    input   logic  ready,
    output  logic  rOut
);

struct packed {
    reg rIn;
    reg rOut;
    reg ready;
} some;

reg rIn;
always @ (posedge clk) begin
    rIn <= ~rIn;
end

always @ (*) begin
    some.rIn = rIn;
    rOut     = some.rOut;
end

always @ (*) begin
    some.ready = ready;
    if (some.ready == 1)
        some.rOut = some.rIn;
end

endmodule
```
The input signal `ready` is equal to 1 during the evaluation, and here is the waveform:
![0](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30991202/101273731-fc456c00-37d2-11eb-9da7-b72733e72b19.JPG)
As you can see, value of packed struct `some`, changes both at the posedge of clk and negedge of clk, which must be wrong.


I think the reason is the same with #2576. In that issue, your workaround is adding commnet `/*verilator_split_var*/`, which is useful to that case, but useless to this one.

I know it's a long term work to fix this bug, but can you add some mechanisms to get this around. For example, make `/*verilator_split_var*/` work when using packed struct.
